      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Stunning Guggenheim, but in the Wrong Place</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Patricia J Scharlin letter comments on November 29 editorial on proposed new Guggenheim Museum in Lower Manhattan</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An East River Guggenheim'' (editorial, Nov. 29):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An East River Guggenheim'' (editorial, Nov. 29):</p>
        <p>Regarding the proposed Frank O. Gehry design for Lower Manhattan, I hope that the planners and consultants doing the environmental impact assessment will heed the warnings of weather scientists that global warming already under way will cause a sea-level rise. This could undermine the whole waterfront structure and public space if not taken into consideration.</p>
        <p>Moreover, increased hurricanes and windstorms could play havoc with the spectacular titanium exterior that Mr. Gehry has proposed. Our city will be the richer for having such an imaginative building, but we want it to be there for our grandchildren and theirs as well.</p>
        <p>PATRICIA J. SCHARLIN  New York, Nov. 30, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a consultant on international environmental policy.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
